<subSubSection id="C34665385B43A91B3BD836EDFD0FFD03" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE336B35B43A91B3BD836EDFD0FFD03" blockId="38.[151,1436,343,656]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B928EAA15B43A91B3BD836EDFEBFFE51" bold="true" box="[199,315,452,477]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species could be distinguished from its congeners by: 1) body dark brown with lighter colored antennae and tarsi; 2) temples slightly dilated; 3) frontal and anteocular furrow superficial; 4) the impunctate longitudinal median band with the width of 
<quantity id="4CA49B565B43A91B39603525FD62FDAF" box="[639,742,524,549]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="0.25">0.25 mm</quantity>
; 5) interspaces between punctures 2–3 punctures’ diameter; 6) admedian row on pronotum of 16–17 punctures, mixed with some smaller punctures besides; 7) mesoscutellum covered with obvious polygonal reticulum; 8) each side of elytra bearing 9–10 rows of small punctures; 9) paired rows of larger spines in 4/5 part of inner sac.
</paragraph>
